9 tar ēis an fhuar - chreidimh do chur ar gcūl :
“ after abandoning the false faith ” . With this use of fuar cf . fuar - chrādhbhadh 184 . Note the construction with gen . after tar ēis ;
similarly , do chum an t - saothair - sin do dhul a dtarbha 36 , and 247 , a dtimcheall dhroch - chreidimh do sgris 61 , tar ēis an rīgh agas na n - Eigifteach uile do bhāthadh 172 , do chum ghlōire agas onōra do thabhairt do Dhia 443 , tar ēis an chūraim - sin do ghabhāil orra 685 , and so frequently . For the undeclined noun in this position cf . do chum a fhios do bheith againd 1764 , and Des . p . 266 .

181 dār thinnsgain tū … dā raibhe oraibh :
the generalising relative dá ( dár with the preterite tense ) after an antecedent qualified by gach ;
in the second case the antecedent is not explicitly qualified but the sense is “ whatever danger ” . Note the singular pronoun tú and the plural oraibh referring to the same person in the same sentence . The use of the pl . is a mark of respect but Carswell does not use it at all consistently ; cf . Des . p . 251 . On the other hand he intermittently uses the first pl . of himself , e . g . do rāidheamar romhaind 180 , but ní fuil a n - ainbfis damh - sa 195 , where the pl . would not have the same meaning . Cf . also dhaoibh - se … dhuit - se 217 - 8 , ar nGaoidhealg … mo dheagh - thoil uaim - se 228 - 9 , ribh … dhuit 265 - 8 .

215 dhā iarraidh :
the equivalent of agá iarraidh and parallel to ag nochtadh ;
cf . Bergin ’ s Stories from Keating ’ s History of Ireland , p . 81 , and CDIL s . v . 1 do 172 . 55 . Similarly dā chrīochnughadh 320 “ being completed ” , atā siad do dheilbh 1612 , neoch ata tú anois do smachtughadh 2576 .

262 timpiridhe :
pl . of timpire ;
cf . CDIL s . v . timthire “ servant ” , and for - mp - ibid . 176 . 4 , . 9 , . 31 , . 44 - 5 , . 56 .

404 dó soirbhidh sén :
impv . 2 sg . , better soirbhigh ;
“ speed good fortune ( or , blessing ) to him . ”

515 do ridhise :
occurs only here for Carswell ’ s usual a rís ;
for the etymology , which justifies this spelling , see DIL s . v . frithissi 442 . 41 .

564 do chomhall :
only here and at 629 gan a comhall ;
the sense appears to be “ fulfil , perform ” . Cf . CIL s . v . comall , and TSh 6138 .

614 ag tarcaisne :
for tarcaisne as a quasi verbal noun cf . CDIL s . v . tarcaisne 78 . 70 ; similarly at 909 with dímheas ,
though both are nouns at 896 .

648 gnúis fri gnúis :
the use of fri in these three phrases is a conscious archaism for the normal ré ;
cf . DIL s . v . fri 413 . 79 .

704 bhus cosmhula … rēna gcosmhala :
in the first case “ suitable ” as parallel to cubhaidh ,
in the second “ likely ” . Carswell realistically omits the phrase “ if there be choice ” ( of candidates for the vacancy ) but retains the examination by ministers and elders ;

767 go dītheallach :
for other examples of palatal th for ch see in the Glossary , s . vv . deith , dītheall , fithead , fitheadmhadh ,
and cf . note 3194 .

1028 do pfrēmhughadh :
for initial p - in this word cf . Keating ’ s History II 5792 . Carswell elsewhere has f - , as 577 , 621 , 2601 . The spelling pf - for lenited p - is unusual , though fp - and fph - are not uncommon ; e . g . CC 16 b 5 do fhulaing an fpháis fa Fpuinge Fphioláid ,
probably taken direct from the Irish Prayer Book ff . IIi verso , kkk2 , and LLL 2 , which also has an Fphosda f . NNn verso . Possibly

1803 macacht ochta :
“ adoption ” , i . e . the state of being a mac ochta ;
cf . CC 46 b 2 , and note 1648 .

2052 go n - aideōmhaidh sé :
fut . of admháil ;
Carswell has - mh - here and in the verbal noun , otherwise - bh - .

2354 ōs ciond ēisg na fairrge :
‘ over … the fishes of the sea ’ , so that we might expect iasg ;
but iasg is collective as well as sg . , as is exemplified in the Sc . G . rendering of Psalm 8 . 8 , where the same idea is expressed , as eunlaith nan speur agus iasg na mara ( where the Modern Irish version has éisc na farraige ) . Cf . , however , mar tugais … ēisg na fairrge 3852 .

3150 oraind :
for oram ;
the pl . is not appropriate to the speaker here , nor is this a congregational prayer .

3379 ōna peacaibh :
‘ from their sins ’ , and so probably to be corrected to bpeacaibh ;
but the strict concord with Eagluis is also possible , and is therefore retained in the text , though the pl . is evidenced elsewhere , as 2768 note .
